snippet.textDisplay: Oh man... I love Cats. It is my favorit musical but tbh I already knew the movie would be bad. I will stil watch it because the music is great and I love dance movies... But the broadway musical that you can buy on DVD is just the top for me. I have even seen the mucial live in theaters here in Germany but nothing tops the DVD version. Sounds like the movie couldn't tell the 'story'. The jellicle cats are a pack of cats who all come to the jellical ball where they try to gain the chance to get a new live/ get into cat heaven. So they all competet for this opportunity by introducing themselves and tell their story and to see who deserve this chance. And then there is Macavaty ... The 'bad' stray cat who interupts the ball out of different reasons. Because of rivalry, because he wants one of the female cats and because he challange the pack leader and even kidnapps him to stop the ball... Because he is an ashole cat 😂  Off cause it is a homage to all the cats out there, too, because the jellicals are somehow stereotyps for different cat personalities.... I don't know yet what the movie did what the story but I will find out soon, I guess. My problem is that the cats don't look like cats. The broadway costumes were so much better... Why didn't the cats have fuzzy hair? They had no fur on their heads at all and that made them look really disturbing somehow... Meh. And there was no main character... Meh. Just meh.

snippet.textDisplay: While I do not doubt that this movie will be an abomination, I'm baffled again and again by reviewers complaining about the lack of plot and how cats are introduced and then they vanish from the story...  Yes, that's exactly how the play works. The cats propose a question at the beginning of the show - who will die and go to the Heavyside Layer? And then each cat comes out, tells their story, and leaves - and the audience is left wondering which one will be reborn... and finally they answer that questions at the end. That's the entire show in a nutshell. The Broadway/West End shows are designed as vehicles for music and dance. And the live show is far more music than (what I've seen of) the movie. It's basically an opera... or pop opera... in the way that Jesus Christ Superstar is a rock opera. That was my first complaint when I saw the trailer - they added dialogue for the dumbed-down middle-American film audience. But for a reviewer to say it "has no plot," well then, you also need to go back and complain about the Broadway show as well... one of the longest-running Broadway shows of all time. I just love that people think they've found the fatal flaw in Cats... 40 years too late. lol. All that being said, yes... it looks like a silly mess. That's because reality expectations are very different for a film as for live theater. We are fine with people in costumes dancing around on stage... but not so much in a film where we have become accustomed to precise realism.  Would this have worked better as a fully animated film? Cartoonish? Or even Lion King style? Idk.
